#Logistic Regression without sklearn
#We would be comparing whether Life Expectancy at birth in years can predict the GDP of a country
X = df['SP_DYN_LE00_IN'].values
Y = df['NY_GDP_MKTP_KD_ZG'].values
#Calculating the mean values
avg_x = np.mean(X)
avg_y = np.mean(Y)
In [13]:
#Calculating the slope and the y-intercept
m = len(X)
num = 0
den = 0
for j in range(m):
  num += (X[j] - avg_x) * (Y[j] - avg_y)
  den += (X[j] - avg_x) ** 2
m = num / den
c = avg_y - (m * avg_x)
print (f'Slope = {m} \nY_intercept = {c}')

Slope = 0.005241519452902699 
Y_intercept = 1.716938286508546
In [14]:
# Visualising the data points and the line of regression
high_x = np.max(X) + 100
low_x = np.min(Y) - 100
x = np.linspace (low_x, high_x, 100)
y = c + m * x
plt.scatter(X, Y, c='red', label='Data Points')
plt.plot(x, y, color='blue', label='Line of Regression')
plt.xlabel('Life Expectancy at birth')
plt.ylabel('GDP of the country')
plt.legend()
plt.show()
In [15]:
#Calculating the R-squared value of the model
sumsqr_t = 0 
sumsqr_r = 0 
val_count=len(df.index)
for j in range(int(val_count)): 
  y_pred = c + m * X[j]
  sumsqr_t += (Y[j] - avg_y) ** 2
  sumsqr_r += (Y[j] - y_pred) ** 2
r2 = 1 - (sumsqr_r/sumsqr_t)
print("R-squared score is:",r2)

R-squared score is: 0.0029099089149056123
